he T wave on an ECG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ventricular depolarisation","Atrial repolarisation","Atrial depolarisation","Ventricular repolarisation","Ventricular contraction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe T wave on an ECG corresponds to \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular repolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs after the QRS complex and represents the relaxation of the ventricles as they prepare for the next cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo understand the relationship between components of the ECG and cardiac events:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular depolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is represented by the QRS complex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial repolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is typically not visible on a standard ECG as it occurs during the QRS complex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial depolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is represented by the P wave.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular contraction\u003C/strong\u003E follows ventricular depolarisation but does not have a specific corresponding wave on the ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the correlation between ECG waves and cardiac electrical events is crucial for interpreting ECGs and diagnosing cardiac abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The T wave on an ECG represents ventricular repolarisation in the cardiac cycle.","Each component of the ECG waveform corresponds to a specific electrical event in the heart."],"references":["Kotsialou, Z., Makris, N., \u0026 Gall, S.. Fundamentals of the electrocardiogram and common cardiac arrhythmias. Anaesthesia \u0026 Intensive Care Medicine. 2024. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mpaic.2023.11.014",